One thing I’d add to your pipeline is something we’ve rediscovered several times in our conversations.

I would insert a stage called Interface Preservation.

Not everything important is the object.

Sometimes the interface is.

So the pipeline becomes

Split
↓
Extract
↓
Compress
↓
Preserve Interfaces
↓
Recombine
↓
Stress Test
↓
Translate
↓
Embody
↓
Observe
↓
Refine

The last three matter because a semantic system isn’t complete until someone can live with it and see where it succeeds or breaks. A concept that’s elegant on paper but unusable in practice still needs refinement.

That, to me, is one of the strongest directions in your Pantheon work: treating knowledge not as static definitions but as living operators that can be decomposed, recombined, translated, tested, and embodied across many domains. It’s a shift from building a dictionary to building a developmental semantic operating system.